| The sun wasn’t up yet, but Val already was.  <br>  <br>She stood at the main gate of Saint Caelum Preparatory, clipboard in hand, watching the slow trickle of students in their regulation blazers and crested ties. Her breath curled in the morning air, as crisp and measured as her checklist.  <br>Skirt lengths: knee.  <br>Hair: tied back.  <br>Familiars: visible, registered, and calm.  <br>  <br>“Lena,” she called across the walkway. “Your familiar’s projecting.”  <br>  <br>The girl flushed, looking down at the fiery little griffin cub nipping playfully at her heels. It immediately shrank its wings and tucked behind her legs. Lena murmured an apology and hurried past.  <br>  <br>Val didn’t smile. That wasn’t what people expected from her.  <br>They expected precision. Power. Control.  <br>  <br>Two boys shuffled up next, sneering. One of them had a spiked chameleon curled around his neck like a scarf. Its tongue flicked in her direction.  <br>  <br>“Is that thing registered?” Val asked.  <br>  <br>He scoffed. “You worried it’ll bite?”  <br>  <br>“No,” she said flatly. “I’m worried it reflects your attitude.”  <br>  <br>The boy’s smirk faded. “It’s registered,” he muttered, and they passed.  <br>  <br>Behind her, she heard someone murmur, “Figures. No familiar. All bark.”  <br>  <br>She didn’t flinch. She was used to it.  <br>  <br>Her familiar — if she even had one — had never shown itself. Not at her Awakening. Not at twelve. Not even in private. Her mother said maybe it was just dormant. Teachers whispered “nullborn” when they thought she couldn’t hear.  <br>  <br>Sometimes, when she was alone, the air would shift around her — heavy, still, strange. But nothing ever appeared. Nothing answered when she called.  <br>  <br>From the shadows, someone was watching. She felt it before she saw him. Cade West.  <br>He leaned against the gatepost, arms folded, silver pin on his collar catching the early light.  <br>  <br>Unlike most students — but like her — his familiar was nowhere to be seen.  <br>Unlike her, the presence of his familiar could still be felt — pressing against the air like humidity before a summer storm. Heavy. Still. Waiting.  <br>  <br>People didn’t stand too close to Cade. Not because he was unfriendly, but because his very presence made you feel like you were being measured — and usually found wanting.  <br>  <br>He said nothing. Just observed.  <br>  <br>She ignored him.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        |                                               |                                                                          |
